\f0\fs20 \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 Once the bones of the player were in place, it was time for the soul: visuals.\
The earliest visualizations were crafted in CoreAnimation, with a laser focus (pun intended) on creating the most stunning audio scope I could. It had to be spline-based, super-fast, and open to rich visual feedback effects. That\'92s where things got geeky\'97in the best possible way.\
The heart of it? A spline algorithm running in Metal Shader Language. Wildly over-engineered? Probably. But completely worth it. Most of the animation work is split between CoreImage and CoreAnimation, which are blisteringly fast and ideal for real-time audio visualization.\
Stylistically, PlayEm leans heavily into an early '80s amber monitor vibe, which pairs beautifully with the texture feedback visuals\'97giving the whole interface a warm, analog glow that feels both retro and futuristic.
